When and how did the idea of internet come around and how did it look in the beginning?
A. In the 1960s, as a military research project. B. In the 1990s, as a commercial venture. C. In the 1980s, as a government initiative. D. In the 1970s, as an academic pursuit. E. In the 2000s, as a social media platform.; A
The idea of the internet came around in the 1960s as a military research project, known as ARPANET, to create a decentralized communication network that could withstand a nuclear attack. It looked very different in the beginning compared to what we see today.
What is the common language TCP/IP and set rules within it that computers follow when communicating with each other?
A. HTML and CSS. B. JavaScript and Python. C. TCP and IP. D. HTTP and FTP. E. XML and JSON.; C
The common language is TCP/IP, which stands for Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol. It sets the rules for how data is transmitted over the internet and how computers communicate with each other.
How does this differ from the OSI reference model?
A. OSI has 5 layers, while TCP/IP has 7 layers. B. OSI is used for hardware communication, while TCP/IP is for software. C. OSI is a protocol, while TCP/IP is a language. D. OSI is used for email communication, while TCP/IP is for web browsing. E. OSI is for mobile networks, while TCP/IP is for wired networks.; A
The OSI reference model has 7 layers, while TCP/IP has 4 layers. This is a key difference between the two models.
What are the principles under which IP based common sets of rules and languages work and what kind of services do they provide?
A. They work on the principle of centralized control and provide file sharing services. B. They work on the principle of decentralized control and provide email services. C. They work on the principle of addressing and routing and provide network connectivity services. D. They work on the principle of encryption and provide security services. E. They work on the principle of data storage and provide cloud services.; C
IP-based common sets of rules and languages work on the principle of addressing and routing, providing network connectivity services. These principles allow data packets to be routed across networks to their intended destinations.
