B. Frames
C. Packets
D. Datagrams
E. Bits; D
Data packets within the internet layer in the TCP/IP reference model are referred to as datagrams.
Which protocol provides a connectionless and unreliable service at the internet layer in the TCP/IP reference model?
A. ARP
B. RARP
C. ICMP
D. IP
E. IGMP; D
IP provides a connectionless and unreliable service, known as 'best-effort delivery service,' at the internet layer in the TCP/IP reference model.
How many addresses does a computer in a network have, according to the TCP/IP reference model?
A. One
B. Two
C. Three
D. Four
E. Five; B
A computer in a network, according to the TCP/IP reference model, has two addresses—a physical address and a logical address.
Which protocol is responsible for mapping a logical address to a physical address in the TCP/IP reference model?
A. IP
B. ARP
C. ICMP
D. RARP
E. IGMP; B
The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) is responsible for mapping a logical address to a physical address in the TCP/IP reference model.
What is the function of the ARP protocol in the TCP/IP reference model?
A. Translate physical addresses to logical addresses
B. Translate logical addresses to physical addresses
C. Report transmission errors to the sender
D. Report transmission errors to a group of users
E. None of the above; B
The ARP protocol is used to translate logical (IP) addresses to physical (MAC) addresses.
Which protocol is used for reporting transmission errors to the sender in the TCP/IP reference model?
A. ARP
B. RARP
C. ICMP
D. IGMP
E. None of the above; C
The ICMP Protocol is used for reporting transmission errors to the sender, such as network delays, attacks, and congestion.
What is the function of the IGMP protocol in the TCP/IP reference model?
A. Translate physical addresses to logical addresses
B. Translate logical addresses to physical addresses
C. Report transmission errors to the sender
D. Report transmission errors to a group of users
E. None of the above; D
The IGMP protocol is used to report transmission errors to a group of users.
What protocols are used by the Transport Layer in the TCP/IP reference model?
A. HTTP and FTP
B. TCP and UDP
C. IP and ICMP
D. SMTP and POP3
E. TCP and SSL; B
The Transport Layer in the TCP/IP reference model uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as its main protocols for reliability, flow control, and data correction.
What is the main difference between TCP and UDP?
A. TCP provides unreliable, connectionless service, while UDP provides reliable, connection-oriented service.
B. TCP adds port address, checksum, and length information to the data packet, while UDP does not.
C. TCP ensures that the packet will reach the right process in the destination node, while UDP does not.
D. TCP is used for applications that do not require sequencing and flow control, while UDP is used for applications that require sequencing and flow control.
E. TCP is slower than UDP in data transmission.; D
The main difference between TCP and UDP is that TCP is used for applications that do not require sequencing and flow control, while UDP is used for applications that require sequencing and flow control. UDP provides unreliable, connectionless service and adds the port address, checksum, and length information to the data packet received from the higher layer.
