What does the 4-bit version field in IP protocol refer to?
A. Total length of the datagram as 4-byte words
B. Header length of the datagram
C. IP protocol version
D. Size of the header when the optional field is empty
E. Size of the header when the optional field is fully used; C
The 4-bit version field in IP protocol refers to the IP protocol version, currently two versions available IPv4 and IPv6.
How is the header length (HLEN) defined in the IP protocol?
A. 20 bytes when the optional field is empty
B. 60 bytes when the optional field is fully used
C. 5 (as 5 x 4 = 20) when the optional field is empty
D. 15 (15 x 4 = 60) when the optional field is fully used
E. Total length of the datagram as 4-byte words; C
The header length (HLEN) is defined as a 4-bit field, defining the total length of the datagram as 4-byte words. When the optional field is empty, the size of the header is 20 bytes and the value of the field is 5 (as 5 x 4 = 20).
What is the 8 bit field in an IPv4 datagram packet used for?
A. To store the source and destination IP addresses
B. To indicate the type of service (TOS) and priority
C. To determine the packet size
D. To store the payload data
E. To identify the packet sequence number; B
The 8 bit field in an IPv4 datagram packet is used to indicate the type of service (TOS) and priority. The first 3 bits are called precedence, the next 4 bits are for type of service (TOS), and the last bit is not used.
What is the purpose of the precedence values 0 to 7 in an IPv4 datagram packet?
A. To represent the source and destination ports
B. To determine the packet routing path
C. To indicate the priority of the datagram
D. To control the packet encryption
E. To identify the packet checksum; C
The precedence values 0 to 7 in an IPv4 datagram packet represent the priority of the datagram. Datagram with the lowest priority (value 0) is discarded first.
What does TOS refer to in the context of IP-based protocols and services?
A. Type of Services
B. TOS Bits
C. Datagram Packet
D. IPv4
E. Source of the image/table; B
TOS stands for Type of Services in the context of IP-based protocols and services.
