A. Used to indicate the type of packet
B. Ignored and not used
C. Reserved for future use
D. Used for error checking
E. Used to identify the destination of the packet; B
The last two bits in the code point subfield of Differentiated services are not used and are ignored.
In what ways can the code point be used in Differentiated services?
A. To determine the precedence bits and identify the source of the packet
B. To represent the service type and differentiate between IPv4 and IPv6 packets
C. To indicate the type of packet and used for error checking
D. To prioritize packet delivery and indicate the destination of the packet
E. To reserve bandwidth and manage network congestion; A
The code point in Differentiated services can be used in two different ways: when the three least significant bits (LSB) are 0s in code point, the most significant bits (MSB) are used as precedence bits, and the usage is similar to service type.
What is the purpose of the code point in Differentiated Services for IPv4 Datagram Packet?
A. To define 64 different services
B. To assign 32 service types by IETF
C. To allow local authorities to use specific code points
D. To allocate code points for experimental purposes
E. To differentiate between source and destination IP addresses; A
The code point in Differentiated Services for IPv4 Datagram Packet can define 64 services by using 6 bits (3 LSB and 3 MSB). It is divided into three categories with different purposes as mentioned in the content.
